post_text: We are in Phase 3 of the Technology Plan: Grades 3 - 5 (now), K - 2 (later). 1:1 Chromebook distribution will occur at schools with supply distribution. Hotspots are reserved for families who do not have internet access. Sign up for a hotspot at your child's school, some restrictions apply. Hotspots do not work in remote rural areas - OSPI is working on grant funding to provide internet access for families but the details are not finalized yet. post_text:
Thank you to the Marysville Together Coalition for supporting youth and families in our Marysville and Tulalip community by sharing information and providing training and resources on the many issues that can impact our youth and families. As school gets underway and students begin to build connections in their virtual classrooms, this helpful article shares insights on being thoughtful, informed, and brave about race.
#MSDCares #MTCoalition
shared_text:
Marysville Together Coalition
June 24 at 9:12 AM Â·

Wanting to help your children become thoughtful, informed, and BRAVE about race? Make space for your child's respective curiosity. Let your child know that itâs okay to notice skin color and talk about race, whether with respect to toys, characters in books, or in the world. Encourage her to share thoughts, feelings, and experiences by asking questions of her and welcoming her questions. If she makes a negative racial comment, ask, non judgmentally, What makes you say that?

For more information on how to talk to your kids about race: https://www.embracerace.org/resources/16-ways-to-help-children-become-thoughtful-informed-and-brave-about-race

post_text: It is time to register for kindergarten! If your child turns 5 by August 31, they are eligible to enroll. Although school will start remotely in the beginning for the health and safety of students, families, and staff, we are still preparing to welcome our students back to school. Early registration is important for class assignments and communication. Registration is done online at https://www.msd25.org/o/District/page/register-for-school or in person at the Educational Service Center located at 4220 80th Street NE.

post_text: Vaccination Clinic in partnership with The Everett Clinic at Allen Creek Elementary School until 2:30 pm today. Although school will not start as normal, getting immunizations up-to-date now will ensure that your child is ready when school does resume in-person in the future. Our instructional teams are working hard to develop plans for remote learning which will look much different than in the Spring. Stay connected for updates and information at www.msd25.org. #MSD25Together #LiveWithJodi

MSD Spotlight: Regional Apprenticeship Pathways (RAP) Program Receives State Pre-Apprenticeship Certification

The WA State Apprenticeship & Training Council (WSATC) officially recognized the Regional Apprenticeship Pathways (RAP) program as a state-certified apprenticeship preparation program on July 16, 2020.

Special thanks to Snohomish County Councilmember, Nate Nehring, Everett Community College, multiple trade apprenticeship programs, and our staff who worked tirelessly as part of this collaborative that prepares students for their future in the trades.

Learn more about this recognition by viewing the official press release at https://drive.google.com/file/d/11lAT2RUozQhL0g5E_TvoObOawS_vsRUh/view, or learn more about the program by watching the video at https://vimeo.com/390593945 or visiting the RAP website: https://www.msd25.org/rap-center

Edit: This video has been updated with Closed Captioning*

Students from Marysville Pilchuck and Marysville Getchell High School's Black Student Unions recently collaborated with community leaders to hold a Peaceful March Against Racism in the Marysville and Tulalip community on June 11.

We are proud of our students' efforts to raise awareness about racism and share ideas on how we can improve, together. Earlier this year, the students met with community leaders to connect.

More plans are underway for listening sessions to lead the way for positive change. #WeAreMSD #BLM

post_text:
Observing National Flag Day!

To commemorate the adoption of our flag, the Congress, by joint resolution approved August 3, 1949, as amended (63 Stat. 492), designated June 14 of each year as âFlag Dayâ and requested that the President issue an annual proclamation calling for its observance and for the display of the flag of the United States on all Federal Government buildings. The Congress requested, by joint resolution approved June 9, 1966, as amended (80 Stat. 194), that the President issue annually a proclamation designating the week in which June 14 occurs as âNational Flag Weekâ and calling on all citizens of the United States to display the flag during that week.
text:
Observing National Flag Day!

To commemorate the adoption of our flag, the Congress, by joint resolution approved August 3, 1949, as amended (63 Stat. 492), designated June 14 of each year as âFlag Dayâ and requested that the President issue an annual proclamation calling for its observance and for the display of the flag of the United States on all Federal Government buildings. The Congress requested, by joint resolution approved June 9, 1966, as amended (80 Stat. 194), that the President issue annually a proclamation designating the week in which June 14 occurs as âNational Flag Weekâ and calling on all citizens of the United States to display the flag during that week.

Sno-Isle Libraries
June 3 at 11:58 AM Â·

The tragic death of George Floyd in Minneapolis combined with current events in our region and across the country present yet another opportunity to examine racism in the U.S.

Public libraries provide resources that help us explore our past, present, and future and build awareness and knowledge. We have gathered for you lists of resources on topics ranging from exploring the history of race in America to materials on anti-racism.

As a community organization made up of community members, Sno-Isle Libraries is actively engaging in efforts related to equity, diversity and inclusion. We are demonstrating our commitment through the adoption of policies, practices, and access to resources that provide opportunities for every person in our community and organization to thrive.
http://ow.ly/m3YZ50zY7fa

Congratulations, MSD Retirees!

Today, May 19, would have been the scheduled retirement celebration for our Marysville School District retirees. Due to the circumstances, we are unable to come together. On behalf of the Marysville School District, please join us in congratulating our retirees for the year 2020.

Click HERE for a slideshow showcasing our retirees.

To this year's retirees, we want to say thank you for all you've given to students, parents, the community and your colleagues. Our wish is for you to enjoy a comfortable and well-deserved time of retirement. We hope the memories of your educational tenure will put a smile on your face and warm your heart.

We wish our retirees all the best!
#WeAreMSD #Happy2020Retirement

#thankateacher #teacherappreciationweek #MarysvilleSchoolDistrict25
shared_text:
Be GLAD
May 7 at 11:04 AM Â·

Hip, Hip, Hooray for Teachers! As part of Teacher Appreciation Week, we are highlighting some of the many fantastic Be GLAD educators and the amazing work they are doing in their school communities.

Annette Northrop is an instructional leader at Allen Creek Elementary school for Marysville School District No. 25 in Washington state. She supports both new teachers and veteran staff as they work to incorporate Be GLAD strategies into their classrooms. Currently, Annette is part of the Be GLAD Trainer in Training (TNT) program and will soon become a Certified Agency Trainer (CAT). Throughout her 15 years as an educator she has worked in many capacities to support learners. Her success comes from co-teaching and teacher collaboration as she strives to provide equitable learning experiences for the students and families she serves. Thank you, Annette!

We appreciate all of the many GLADtastic educators and your commitment to student success.

#thankateacher #teacherappreciationweek #MarysvilleSchoolDistrict25

post_text:
Food Lifeline will distribute emergency food boxes at the Seattle Premium Outlets (Tulalip) on Friday, May 15. Food Lifeline will distribute several thousand emergency food boxes to anyone needing help keeping food on the table during this crisis. The distributions will occur at the following locations and times:

Seattle Premium Outlets (Tulalip) 10600 Quil Ceda Blvd., Tulalip, Wa. 98271
Â· Friday, May 15th, at 3:00 - 5:00 p.m.
These emergency food boxes each contain 22-25 lbs of shelf-stable food items like canned fruits and vegetables, canned meats, non-meat protein items, and bread and grains. They will also contain some fresh produce items that tend to have a longer shelf life. Those wishing to take home boxes can receive a drive-up no-touch distribution, and there will also be walk-up distribution. ANYONE can have access to this food. This is a confidential distribution, so there will be no paperwork or qualification. Food Lifeline is only asking for zip codes to track its efforts.

post_text:
Happy National School Nurse Day

Today is National School Nurse Day
Since 1972, National School Nurse Day has been set aside to recognize school nurses. This year we want to send a special thank you to our nurses who have shown up each and every day for our students.

National School Nurse Day was established to foster a better understanding of the role of school nurses. The next you encounter our nurses be sure to thank them for their role in educating and taking care of our students.

National School Nurse Day is celebrated on the Wednesday within National Nurse Week, which is May 6th - May 12th each year.

Learn more about National School Nurse day at https://www.nasn.org/advocacy/school-nurse-day

post_text:
HAPPY CINCO DE MAYO

Cinco de Mayo, or the fifth of May, is a holiday that celebrates the date of the Mexican armyâs May 5, 1862 victory over France at the Battle of Puebla during the Franco-Mexican War. The day, which falls on Tuesday, May 5 in 2020, is also known as Battle of Puebla Day. While it is a relatively minor holiday in Mexico, in the United States, Cinco de Mayo has evolved into a commemoration of Mexican culture and heritage, particularly in areas with large Mexican-American populations.

Learn more about Cinco de Mayo history at https://www.history.com/topics/holidays/cinco-de-mayo

The Marysville School District is so thankful to each of the Marysville and Tulalip community partners who have joined us in our efforts to address and meet the needs of our students, families, and the greater community.

post_text:
April 22nd, 2020, marks the 50th anniversary of Earth Day.

Earth Day was founded in 1970 as a day of education about environmental issues.

The holiday is now a global celebration thatâs sometimes extended into Earth Week, a full seven days of events focused on green living. The brainchild of Senator Gaylord Nelson and inspired by the protests of the 1960s, Earth Day began as a ânational teach-in on the environmentâ and was held on April 22 to maximize the number of students that could be reached on university campuses.

By raising public awareness of pollution, Nelson hoped to bring environmental causes into the national spotlight.

Learn more about earth day at: https://www.history.com/topics/holidays/earth-day

Happy Earth Day, Remember to take a moment to appreciate the natural and unique beauty found only here on Earth!

#Earthday #Everydayisearthday

This week in our discussion with loved ones, we should focus on the people in our lives whose connection brings us warmth. Is there anyone that comes to mind that you may want to reach out to? Can be in your home or far away. Although we may not be able to share company with many people at this time, we can still reach out and show them we care.

If you enjoyed discussing this conversation starter with your loved ones, you can find more conversation starters on our website at www.marysvilletogether.org

March 26 at 4:58 PM Â·

Marysville School District staff distributed over 1,000 laptops to their elementary-aged families at today's drive-up Chromebook Checkout. From young Kindergartners to veteran 5th graders, so many of the students were ecstatic to see their teachers and school staff.

Students also received an assortment of school supplies and hygiene kits to reduce the financial burden their families may be going through during this unprecedented school closure.

Marysville Together Coalition
March 25 at 10:00 AM Â·

To continue our valuable discussions with our loved ones, this week we have another conversation starter for you all! This week we want to focus on how well we connect with each other, especially in these times of unknowing. How often do you give someone your undivided attention? Giving someone your focus to understand their point of view is a great way to get to know someone from their perspective.

If you enjoyed discussing this conversation starter with your loved ones, you can find more conversation starters on our website at marysvilletogether.org

Stay healthy, be safe, be wise! #MarysvilleTogether

post_text:
First Legacy High School Nationwide Coding Award!

Legacy High School Student, David Perez recently placed in the Top 100 songs in a nationwide Amazon Future Engineer Ea rSketch Ciara Remix coding Competition .
There were over 1200 entries from 32 states. Winners were chosen by a panel of judges who are experts in music technology, composition, computer science, and STEM education .
Learn more about this competition at https://www.teachers.earsketch.org/top-100-winners for EarSketch in your classroom and access to more computer science resources to continue your students' journey into coding.

Congratulations David, we are very proud of you!

Family Survey - Please Respond by March 16, 2020
When Governor Inslee closed schools, he directed school districts to work on plans for continued food service for children and childcare for healthcare workers and first responders in the community.

As a district, we are also exploring how we can support students and families with enrichment activities to do at home during this extended closure.

Please take a few moments to fill out this form, so we can plan appropriately.

Click https://bit.ly/38S12Wm to access the survey. Please respond by March 16.

post_text:
Meet Irista Reeves

Irista is a Heritage High School student who is taking art classes at Legacy High School. Her artwork recently made it into the Scholastic Art Show hosted at the Schack Art Center in Everett.

Below is Irista's artist statement:

"The earth around us speaks to me. It shows me beauty within the darkness. It shows me everything I know. I naturally gather ideas then piece them together. It appears in my head so fast like a snowball rolling down a mountain. Just getting bigger and becoming unstoppable. I try to capture everything I see, something that holds value. Certain individuals have a strong impression on me, and that in turn inspires me in my art. I want to display all the smiles and the people that make me happy."

Way to go, Irista, your work speaks to us and we are proud of you!

post_text:
The Future Chef event planned for March 19 is canceled

In an effort to help prevent the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19, the Marysville School District has canceled all scheduled events that occur outside of the school day. The District's Child Nutrition Services staff will continue to work with our schools and partners for future planning for the Future Chefs event.

We would like to thank our students, staff, and partners for the time and effort put into planning thus far and for their continued work with students and schools to provide opportunities where each and every student and their families feel welcomed and supported.

The District continues to closely monitor this rapidly evolving health concern and will continue to follow the guidelines of the Snohomish Health District.

Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds

Avoid touching eyes, nose, or mouth with unwashed hands

Avoid contact with people who are sick

Stay home while sick and avoid close contact with others

Cover mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing, then throw the tissue in the trash and wash hands

As CTE Month comes to a close, here is a look into our Regional Apprenticeship Pathways program.

The RAP program is offered to students interested in gaining pre-apprenticeship skills in the areas of carpentry, electrical, and labor. Students will gain valuable transferable skills leading to industry certification, college credit and certification as well as preferred entry into a professional apprenticeship. High school students will learn alongside students from surrounding districts as well as college students offering higher engagement in real-world career-focused instruction. Students will spend an extended period of time, participating in either a morning or afternoon session (3 periods per day) on projects allowing for deeper levels of understanding and experiential learning. Previous construction coursework or experience is advantageous but not required.

Learn more at: http://marysvillewa.apptegy.us/o/district/page/rap-center?mode=edit
text:
As CTE Month comes to a close, here is a look into our Regional Apprenticeship Pathways program.

The RAP program is offered to students interested in gaining pre-apprenticeship skills in the areas of carpentry, electrical, and labor. Students will gain valuable transferable skills leading to industry certification, college credit and certification as well as preferred entry into a professional apprenticeship. High school students will learn alongside students from surrounding districts as well as college students offering higher engagement in real-world career-focused instruction. Students will spend an extended period of time, participating in either a morning or afternoon session (3 periods per day) on projects allowing for deeper levels of understanding and experiential learning. Previous construction coursework or experience is advantageous but not required.

Learn more at: http://marysvillewa.apptegy.us/o/district/page/rap-center?mode=edit
